<h1>Local-First Software Weekly</h1>
<p>Welcome to the first issue of this newsletter about local-first software.
The core idea of local-first software is that your data lives on your own
devices first, and the network is used for synchronization rather than as
the primary home of your information. This gives users ownership, offline
capability, and longevity that cloud-only applications cannot match.</p>
<p>This week we look at how reading applications handle data ownership.
Most read-it-later services store your library on their servers, which
means the day the company shuts down, your archive disappears with it.
A local-first reader keeps markdown files on disk, uses an embedded
database for metadata, and treats any cloud component as an optional
convenience rather than a requirement for daily use.</p>
