<p>We also examine synchronization strategies. Conflict-free replicated
data types allow multiple devices to edit the same notes without a central
coordinator, while simpler last-write-wins semantics are often good enough
for metadata like read status and ratings. The engineering trade-off is
between implementation complexity and the actual frequency of concurrent
edits in a single-user system.</p>
<p>Finally, a short note on portability. Plain files in open formats are
the most durable escape hatch an application can offer. If your notes are
markdown and your metadata is a SQLite file, you can leave at any time,
and paradoxically that freedom is what makes staying attractive.</p>
